# Line-ending discipline.
#
# third_party/ is VENDORED, byte-pinned code: the minix dependency-surface
# ratchet (tools/test_minix_dependency_surface.sh) SHA-256-pins
# third_party/nlohmann/json.hpp, so git must NEVER rewrite its bytes.
# Without this rule, a checkout on a machine with core.autocrlf=true (the
# Git-for-Windows default on the GitHub windows-2022 runner) converts the
# header to CRLF, the hash flips (9bea4c80... -> 853b2eb3...), and the ratchet
# goes red on CI while staying green on every autocrlf=false dev box —
# exactly the failure observed on the first full Actions run.
third_party/** -text

# Shell scripts must stay LF: bash parses a CRLF shebang/line as part of the
# token ("\r: command not found" class). Git Bash happens to tolerate most of
# it, but pin it rather than rely on that.
*.sh text eol=lf

# CMake + workflow files: LF for cross-platform hash/diff stability.
CMakeLists.txt text eol=lf
*.cmake text eol=lf
*.yml text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf
